 <img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-53439" src="http://www.nta.ng/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/Nigerian-Ports-Authority-420x236.jpg" alt="" width="420" height="236" srcset="http://www.nta.ng/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/Nigerian-Ports-Authority-420x236.jpg 420w, http://www.nta.ng/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/Nigerian-Ports-Authority-150x84.jpg 150w, http://www.nta.ng/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/Nigerian-Ports-Authority-768x431.jpg 768w, http://www.nta.ng/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/Nigerian-Ports-Authority-720x404.jpg 720w, http://www.nta.ng/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/Nigerian-Ports-Authority.jpg 1000w" sizes="(max-width: 420px) 100vw, 420px" /> A total of 16 ships laden with various products including petrol are at the Lagos Ports waiting to berth, the Nigerian Ports Authority (NPA) said on Wednesday. The NPA disclosed in its daily “Shipping Position” made available to the News Agency of Nigeria (NAN) in Lagos that 14 of the vessels carrying petrol were waiting to berth. It said another two ships would berth with ethanol and bulk fertiliser. No fewer than 34 other ships laden with petroleum products, food items and other goods are expected at Apapa and Tin-Can Island Ports between April 18 and May 6. The expected ships are carrying buck wheat, containers, container, frozen fish, bulk sugar, buck wheat, base oil, bulk fertiliser, general cargo, bulk gypsum, empty containers and petrol. (NAN) Suleiman idris is a graduate of Fed Univ of Tech Minna (BTECH Mathematics/Comp Science), Specialist in ICT Support Services. also proficient in use of online journalism tools & Social media management. I currently serve as I.T Officer with Africa's Largest TV Network NTA